# Performance Rules (Flutter)

Performance is a **core architectural constraint**, not an optimization step.

All UI must target:
- smooth 60fps (16ms/frame budget)
- minimal rebuild scope
- predictable memory usage
- no work inside render pipeline unless necessary

---

# 1. Frame Budget Rules

## Target

- [ ] 16ms per frame (60fps) on standard devices
- [ ] 8ms per frame (120fps) on high-refresh-rate devices
- [ ] avoid jank on scroll, animations, and transitions
- [ ] no blocking synchronous work on UI thread

---

## MUST NOT

- block UI thread with computation
- perform expensive work during build/render
- trigger cascading rebuild chains unintentionally

---

# 2. Widget Rebuild Rules

## Core Principle

> Rebuild only what must change â€” nothing more.

---

## Required Practices

- [ ] use `const` constructors wherever possible
- [ ] split large widgets into smaller sub-widgets
- [ ] isolate rebuild boundaries intentionally
- [ ] prefer composition over deep widget trees

---

## Riverpod Rules

- [ ] use `ref.watch` only where UI depends on state
- [ ] use `ref.select` for fine-grained rebuild control
- [ ] avoid watching large objects unnecessarily
- [ ] avoid provider over-subscription in top-level widgets

---

## MUST NOT

- trigger rebuilds from unrelated state changes
- use broad `watch` when narrow selection is sufficient
- place all state consumption at root widget level

---

# 3. build() Method Rules

## Forbidden in build()

### MUST NOT

- network requests
- file I/O
- database queries
- heavy computation
- provider creation or initialization
- side effects (`setState`, navigation, logging side-effects)

---

## Allowed in build()

- pure UI composition
- lightweight formatting
- state reading (via Riverpod)

---

# 4. Widget Structure Optimization

## Required Practices

- [ ] extract sub-widgets to isolate rebuild regions
- [ ] keep build methods small and readable
- [ ] prefer stateless composition
- [ ] use `const` for static subtrees

---

## Anti-Patterns

- giant monolithic build methods
- deeply nested widget trees without extraction
- recomputing derived values inside build

---

# 5. List & Scroll Performance

## Required Patterns

### Large Lists (>20 items)

- [ ] use `ListView.builder`
- [ ] or `SliverList` / `SliverGrid` in `CustomScrollView`

---

### Fixed-Size Items

- [ ] use `itemExtent` when height is known
- [ ] improves scroll performance significantly

---

### Scroll Rules

- [ ] avoid nested scroll views
- [ ] if nesting required:
  - use `NeverScrollableScrollPhysics`
  - or restructure with slivers

---

## MUST NOT

- use unbounded `ListView` without itemCount
- nest scroll views without explicit control

---

# 6. Memory Management Rules

## Providers

- [ ] use `autoDispose` by default (Riverpod)
- [ ] avoid long-lived unnecessary state
- [ ] clean up listeners and controllers

---

## Controllers

- [ ] dispose `TextEditingController`
- [ ] dispose `AnimationController`
- [ ] dispose `ScrollController`
- [ ] avoid leaks from streams and subscriptions

---

# 7. Rendering Optimization

## Required Practices

- [ ] use `RepaintBoundary` for expensive isolated widgets (only when justified)
- [ ] avoid unnecessary opacity layers
- [ ] prefer `AnimatedOpacity` over heavy rebuild animations
- [ ] cache computed values outside build when possible

---

## MUST NOT

- overuse `Opacity` widget in large trees
- trigger full-screen repaints unnecessarily
- rebuild entire pages for small state changes

---

# 8. Computation Rules

## Allowed

- lightweight formatting
- simple mapping over small lists

## Forbidden

- heavy loops in build()
- expensive filtering/sorting without caching
- repeated computation of derived values per frame

---

## Required Pattern

- move expensive computation into:
  - providers
  - memoized functions
  - domain layer

---

# 9. Image & Asset Performance

- [ ] use correctly sized images (no oversized decoding)
- [ ] use caching where appropriate
- [ ] avoid decoding large assets in UI thread
- [ ] prefer lazy loading for media-heavy screens

---

# 10. Debugging Performance Issues

When diagnosing performance:

- [ ] use Flutter DevTools timeline
- [ ] inspect rebuild frequency
- [ ] identify widget repaint boundaries
- [ ] measure frame times >16ms
- [ ] check Riverpod provider fan-out

---

# 11. Anti-Patterns (DO NOT DO)

## MUST NOT

- heavy computation in build()
- unnecessary provider watching at root level
- rebuilding entire screens for small updates
- unbounded lists
- missing const optimizations
- leaking controllers or streams
- ignoring frame budget violations

---

# 12. Validation Checklist

Before committing:

- [ ] build methods are lightweight
- [ ] rebuild scope minimized
- [ ] lists optimized for performance
- [ ] controllers properly disposed
- [ ] no forbidden operations in build()
- [ ] const used where possible
- [ ] preflight passes